  "local_port": 58172,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "If you and your Argentinean boyfriend get married in the US, he can apply for a green card (permanent residency) through the process known as \"Adjustment of Status\" if he is already in the US. Here's a general overview of the process and timeline:\n\n1. **Marriage and Immediate Steps:**\n   - After getting married, you'll need to gather documents to prove the authenticity of your marriage and your eligibility for the spousal visa. These include marriage certificates, proof of your US citizenship, and evidence of your relationship.\n\n2. **Filing the Petition:**\n   - You, as the US citizen, will need to file Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative) with the United States Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS). This form establishes the relationship between you and your spouse.\n\n3. **Concurrent Filing:**\n   - If your spouse is in the US and entered legally, you can file Form I-130 concurrently with Form I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status). This allows your spouse to apply for a green card without leaving the US.\n\n4. **Work Authorization:**\n   - Along with Form I-485, your spouse can also file Form I-765 (Application for Employment Authorization). This allows them to apply for a work permit (EAD - Employment Authorization Document). Typically, the EAD is granted within 5-7 months after filing.\n\n5. **Timeline:**\n   - The entire process from filing to receiving the green card can take anywhere from 6 months to over a year, depending on the backlog at the USCIS office processing your case.\n   - Once the I-765 is approved, your spouse can start working legally in the US with the EAD.\n\n6. **Interview and Approval:**\n   - After the application is processed, you and your spouse will be called for an interview. If everything goes well, the green card will be approved, and your spouse will receive permanent resident status.\n\n**Important Notes:**\n- The exact timeline can vary based on individual circumstances and the workload of the USCIS office.\n- It's recommended to consult with an immigration attorney to ensure all paperwork is correctly filed and to navigate any complexities that may arise.\n\nIn summary, your Argentinean spouse can potentially start working in the US within about 5-7 months after filing the necessary forms, assuming everything goes smoothly and there are no complications or delays.",
